HEDGEHOGS, DEMYELINATING PARALYSIS - UK (ENGLAND) (02)
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
<http://www.fas.org/ahead>
See Also
Hedgehogs, demyelinating paralysis - UK (England) 981210154815
Date: Sat, 12 Dec 1998 10:13:16 -0600
From: "Howard L. Lipton" <hllipton@merle.acns.nwu.edu>

I would be interested in getting more information, perhaps the
article in the Vet Record. I work with Theiler's virus-induced
demyelinating disease in mice which is a model for multiple
sclerosis. Theiler's virus is a picornavirus that is unusual in that
it persists in the central nervous system of mice which leds to
inflammatory demyelination (the virus can be readily isolated from
the spinal cords of affected mice for many months post infection).
Paraparesis slowly evolves in the mice.
Theiler's virus mainly infects mice in nature, but several other
related rodents may also harbor this virus. Theiler's virus has also
been shown to experimentally infect hamsters, rats and possibly
guinea pigs, but very few studies have been done in these species. We
have a putative receptor protein which is found in the brush border
cells of dogs.
